ENUGU  – A non-governmental organisa­tion (NGO), Women Empow­erment Education And Peace Building Initiative (WEPBI) has unveiled its plan to deal with issues of violence against women. Briefing Journalists on its plan to alleviate pain and pov­erty among women and girls, the Executive Director of WEP­BI, Joy Ijeoma Oguadimma, said “as we all know, violence against women is not new and that’s one of the major reasons why this NGO was created. “We have been tackling is­sues of women that are abused by their intimate partners as well as other gender violence. -Advertisement- “Ending violence against women is everyone’s business and all hands must be on deck to tackle gender violence in our society,” Oguadimma said. WEPBI unveiled the new­ly launched online media TV called “Witness Experience” which will serve as a platform to enable women to share their stories. Oguadimma assured that the newly launched online TV will be used to address all forms of ways women right are being violated as well as offer coun­seling to traumatised women and girls. She reiterated the determi­nation of the organisation to continue to provide financial support to women in the state especially the rural dwellers to enable the to support their fam­ilies and live happy life. ”We have assisted and pro­vided financial support to kick start their business and today they are doing well and happy so we will continue to render helping hands to alleviate pov­erty among women. POLL According to her, the objec­tives of WEPBI is to work with women and girls to participate in all decision-making process­es that advance their rights as well as tackle all gender-relat­ed violence among women and girls.